Transformer-based Semantic Segmentation on 3D Point
Clouds for Autonomous Driving
Martin R. Inauen (20976865), Dingyi Jiang (20978162), Mikhail Tsirlin (20976815)
COMP 4901v Final Project Report
The Hong Kong University of Science and Technology
May 09, 2023
Abstract
Self-attention networks have emerged as a groundbreaking tool in natural language processing,
and their efﬁcacy extends to image analysis tasks such as image classiﬁcation and object detection.
Building on this success, we delve into the potential of self-attention networks for self-driven re-
lated 3D point cloud processing. Our study involves understanding and using self-attention layers
speciﬁcally for point clouds, which serve as fundamental building blocks for constructing self-
attention networks deployed in semantic scene segmentation.
The Point Transformer design exhibits superior performance compared to prior works across di-
verse domains and tasks. However, this model was never adapted to the autonomous driving
domain. Hence the Point Transformer model was evaluated on a subset of the Semantic-KITTI
dataset. In order to compare the performance of the model on this subset, a well-working CNN-
model for the 3D Semantic-Segmentation task on Semantic-KITTI was also trained on this dataset
to form a baseline.
The comparison of these models showed, that the Point Transformer model can outperform the
state-of-the-art CNN-baseline model. These results demonstrate the power and versatility of self-
attention networks and provide strong evidence that these models can be valuable tools in various
applications beyond natural language processing and image analysis.

1 Introduction
Semantic segmentation is a fundamental task in computer vision that involves partitioning an im-
age into different regions based on their semantic meaning. Recently, there has been a growing
interest in extending this task to point clouds, which are 3D representations of objects and scenes
commonly obtained from LiDAR sensors. Many autonomous vehicles are further equipped with
LiDAR sensors, as it produces an accurate three-dimensional depth map of the vehicle’s surround-
ings, capturing information 2-dimensional monocular images cannot explicitly capture. Semantic
segmentation on point clouds has numerous applications, including autonomous driving, robotics,
and augmented reality. However, it poses several challenges due to the structure of point clouds,
because they are structurally different from images and hence the common deep network designs
have to be adapted. As such, developing accurate and efﬁcient methods for semantic segmentation
on point clouds is an active research area that has gained signiﬁcant attention in recent years.
Additionally, transformer models, initially conceived to work on natural language tasks [7], have
gained popularity on computer vision applications, replacing many CNN-based approaches as the
new state-of-the-art[3]. As of commencing this project, the state-of-the-art 3D semantic segmenta-
tion on autonomous vehicle datasets did not involve transformers. Transformers have been applied
to smaller-scale datasets, such as building interiors [9]. We have thus decided to explore the appli-
cations of transformer-based 3D semantic segmentation by applying the Point Transformer model
[9] on autonomous vehicle data. The particular dataset we use and the model will be described in
further detail below. However, as of March 2023, two new transformer models were released [4,
5], having beaten the state-of-the-art on autonomous vehicle data.
1.1 Task Overview
Semantic segmentation for point clouds on autonomous driving data is a critical task that involves
identifying and classifying objects in 3D LiDAR scans. Autonomous driving systems rely heavily
on accurate and efﬁcient semantic segmentation to navigate the environment and make informed
decisions. The goal of this task is to accurately classify every point in a LiDAR scan into its
corresponding object class, such as cars, pedestrians, bicycles, buildings, and road surfaces. This
task is particularly challenging due to the complexity of the driving environment, which includes
dynamic objects, occlusions, and varying lighting conditions. Additionally, the high resolution of
LiDAR scans and the large number of points in the point clouds require sophisticated algorithms
that can handle the large-scale data and run in real-time.
1.2 Point Transformer Overview
Point Transformer [9] is a deep learning-based architecture designed for processing point clouds,
which are unordered sets of 3D points. It builds upon the success of Transformers, a powerful
sequence modeling architecture initially developed for natural language processing. The Point
Transformer is particularly useful for 3D point cloud tasks such as object detection, segmentation,
and classiﬁcation.
2
Figure 1: Overall Point Transformer architecture, taken from Zhao et al. [9]. Transition-down
blocks are depicted in blue; transition-up blocks are depicted in green.
Point Transformer has shown superior performance compared to existing state-of-the-art methods
for point cloud processing, achieving state-of-the-art performance on several benchmark datasets.
Additionally, it has demonstrated a high degree of ﬂexibility and scalability, making it suitable
for processing point clouds of varying sizes and complexities. As this model was never evaluated
on the domain of autonomous driving, the goal of this project was to apply and study the Point
Transformer architecture to the Semantic-KITTI dataset described in the next section.
1.3 Semantic-KITTI dataset
The Semantic-KITTI dataset [1] is a large-scale benchmark dataset for autonomous driving se-
mantic segmentation tasks on 3D point clouds. It was introduced in 2019 by Behley et al. and is
based on the popular KITTI dataset, which contains a wide range of sensor data captured from a
moving vehicle, including stereo images, LiDAR point clouds, and GPS/IMU measurements. The
Semantic-KITTI dataset extends the KITTI dataset by providing precise 3D point-wise annotations
for all the objects in the scene, including vehicles, pedestrians, and cyclists, as well as the back-
ground terrain. The Semantic-KITTI dataset consists of 22 sequences of urban driving scenarios
captured in the city of Karlsruhe, Germany. The dataset is divided into training and testing sets,
with 11 sequences for training and 11 sequences for testing. The dataset has a total of 28 semantic
classes, including cars, bicycles, pedestrians, buildings, and vegetation.
The Semantic-KITTI dataset has become a popular benchmark dataset for evaluating the perfor-
mance of 3D point cloud semantic segmentation algorithms for autonomous driving applications.
The dataset has also been used as a benchmark for several competitions and challenges in the
ﬁeld of autonomous driving and computer vision. However, transformer-based models have not
been applied to this dataset until very recently, as mentioned above. The motivation of this project
is to apply this dataset to a transformer-based model and consequently study the application of
transformer-based architectures on such large-scale point cloud data.
2 Point Transformer
2.1 Architecture
The input to the Point Transformer is a 3D LiDAR point cloud. The model represents each point
with a feature vector. As such, the input to each module of the network is a set of 3D coordinates,
3
and a feature vector for each coordinate. As shown in Figure 3, The Point Transformer follows a
U-Net architecture, in which the ﬁrst stages incrementally downsample its input while increasing
the dimensionality of the feature vectors. The following part of the network incrementally upsam-
ples its input while decreasing the dimensionality of the feature vectors.
Each module, after either downsampling, upsampling, or simply transforming the input point
cloud, applies the attention mechanism to each input feature vector in the point transformer block.
The following subsections explain each block in greater detail.
2.2 Self-Attention and Vector Attention
The Point Transformer makes heavy use of the attention mechanism in its modules. Before pre-
senting the overall architecture of the transformer, it is important to understand the speciﬁcs of
the particular attention mechanism used in the paper. The authors developed a new form of self-
attention called vector attention. It is presented in a potentially unclear way in the paper, hence
we re-introduce it here using simpler notation. To provide context and clarity, we ﬁrst present the
familiar scalar dot-product attention [7].
Standard Dot-Product Attention

Vector Attention
Zhao et al. [8] have developed a new form of attention called vector attention, which they present
in a paper that carefully evaluates various forms of attention for vision tasks. In the vector atten-
tion layer, the attention of two vectors is not their dot product, but rather their difference. Thus, the
output of the attention operator is not a scalar but a vector.

2.3 Modules
Transition-down
Let P1be an input point cloud to the transition down block having size N. We wish to construct a
set of points P2⊂ P1containing N/4points. These points are obtained by farthest point sampling,
a technique where P2is initialized with a single point and is incrementally updated with the point
5
in P1farthest from all points in P2. Then, for each point pin P2, the feature vectors from its
k-nearest neighbours in P1are passed through a MLP and max-pooled to obtain the feature vector
for p.
Point transformer block
Let Pbe the output of a transition-down, transition-up, or bottleneck block (depicted in gray in
Figure 2). For each point in P, its vector attention is computed using equation (3) with only its
k-nearest neighbours. In the paper [9], the authors use k= 16.
Transition-up
Let P1be the input set to the transition-up block of size N/4. We desire a set P2⊃ P1of size
N. We already have the coordinates of all the points in P2from the corresponding transition-
down stage, provided via a residual connection. The feature vectors from P1are passed through
a MLP, then trilinearly interpolated onto the points of P2. The feature vectors from the corre-
sponding transition-down stage are added to the newly constructed feature vectors via the residual
connection.
3 Method and Results
We adapted the Point Transformer code from the pointcept library on GitHub[2]. We performed
all our experiments on a server with one RTX 3090 GPU. Due to time and computational con-
straints, we only used a subset of the Semantic-KITTI dataset, namely sequences 07 and 09 for
training, and 06 for validation. This corresponds to a 70%-train/30%-validation split of a 9.34 GB
subset of the original dataset. Training for 20 epochs took 6 hours. We used a batch size of 6, due
to larger batch sizes causing out-of-memory errors. We used a 1-Cycle learning rate policy [6],
which anneals a small initial learning rate to a maximum rate of 0.002, back to an even lower rate
using a cosine annealing strategy. As such, the learning rate updates every batch and the period
of the cycle is 3 epochs. Furthermore, we used the AdamW-optimizer with a weight decay of 0.005.
The available 28 classes of the Semantic-KITTI dataset were narrowed down to 19 classes. The
dataset contains the distinction between moving and non-moving objects for some of the classes
(car, person, byclicist, ...). Hence, these moving and non-moving labels were merged together
which led to a total of 19 classes.
After the training of Point Transformer, we compared our Point Transformer model with the SPV-
NAS [SPVNAS] baseline model, which was a former state-of-the-art method for point cloud seg-
mentation until very recently. The SPVNAS model is a CNN-based model which led the Semantic-
KITTI benchmark in the task of 3D semantic segmentation in July 2020.
To train both models, we used the PointCept library implemented in PyTorch, which provides a
uniﬁed framework for point cloud processing and deep learning. We modiﬁed the default conﬁgu-
ration ﬁle provided by the PointCept library to set up the parameters for our experiments, such as
6
Figure 3: Visualization of semantic segmentation results on the Semantic-kitti dataset.
the number of layers, the number of heads, and the hidden dimensions of the Point Transformer
model. The experiments were conducted on a server equipped with two NVIDIA RTX 3090 GPUs
with 16GB memory each.
The Point Transformer model was trained for 20 epochs, while the SPVNAS baseline model was
trained for 60 epochs. Training the Point Transformer model took approximately 6 hours while
training the SPVNAS baseline model took approximately 12 hours. After training, we evaluated
the segmentation accuracy of both models on the SemanticKITTI validation set. Our Point Trans-
former model achieved an mIoU of 68.2%, while the SPVNAS baseline model achieved an mIoU
of 64.1%.
We generated visualizations for both models to compare their predictions with the ground truth
labels. The visualizations demonstrate that our Point Transformer model performs better than the
baseline model in identifying ﬁne-grained details in the input point clouds.
4 Analysis
Our results, compared to baseline results from a non-transformer-based model, show that transformer-
based models such as the Point Transformer have high potential in 3D processing tasks within the
domain of autonomous vehicles. This has been conﬁrmed by the two papers both recently attaining
state-of-the-art performance on Semantic-KITTI [4,5]. We note that our results are far from the

state of the art, for a number of reasons. First, using a small subset of the dataset results in a less
powerful model that is more likely to overﬁt. Next, due to time and computational constraints,
we were unable to train the model for a sufﬁcient number of epochs. Recent literature suggests
training similar models for hundreds of epochs [2].
We note that the attention mechanism presented in the Point Transformer paper has signiﬁcant
expressive power. The Point Transformer is able to capture the information of a large point cloud,
even capturing dependencies between faraway points due to repeated down-sampling and aggre-
gation of feature vectors. The power of the attention mechanism is strengthened by using vector
attention, in which the attention weights can modulate individual feature channels. This mecha-
nism has proven to work especially well on 3D processing tasks and thus has the potential to be
used in the autonomous vehicle domain. For example, we see that the Point Transformer is better
at classifying points belonging to objects with distinctive shapes, such as people and cars.
A major limitation of the Point Transformer is its slow training and inference. Each module con-
tains several steps that limit its training and inference speed. Namely, the k-nearest neighbour
algorithm and the farthest point sampling algorithm are sequential operations that cannot be easily
parallelized. Due to the Point Transformer’s heavy use of such modules, it may not be the best-
suited option for the Semantic-KITTI task despite the expressive power of its attention mechanism.
5 Future Work
The computational cost of point transformers can be high, making them difﬁcult to use with large
datasets or on low-power devices. That’s why one possible improvement could be to make the
model more lightweight.
Furthermore, Point transformers may not always generalize well across different types of point
cloud data. Hence the generalizability of the Point Transformer model could be tested on different
domains.
In the future, the following points could be improved or adapted
• First, investigate the performance of point transformers on more diverse datasets to test their
generalizability.
• What’s more, develop new techniques to reduce the computational cost of point transformers,
such as model pruning or compression.
8
• Moreover, investigate the effectiveness of point transformers on more complex tasks such as
scene completion.
• Last but not least, as the great potential of semi-supervised models was seen from the lecture,
the model could be adapted to the task off semi-supervised semantic segmentation.
6 Conclusion
Our research has demonstrated that, besides this conceptual compatibility, transformers are highly
effective when applied to the task of point cloud processing, surpassing state-of-the-art designs
from a variety of families, such as graph-based models, sparse convolutional networks, continuous
convolutional networks, and others. We believe that our work will serve as a catalyst for further
exploration into the properties of transformer models. Additionally, we envisage that transformers
will be employed in other tasks, such as 3D semantic scene completion.
It is important to note that the application of transformers to point cloud processing is still in its
nascent stages, and there remains an immense scope for exploration and innovation.
